  "slug": "rosol",
  "title": "Rosół",
  "subtitle": "Polish clear chicken broth",
  "excerpt": "A long-simmered chicken broth with root vegetables, a charred onion, and aromatic spices, the clearest, most restorative soup in Polish cooking. Served over egg noodles every Sunday.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Rosół is the foundational soup of Polish home cooking, the Sunday meal across all classes and generations. Documented in Maria Lemnis and Henryk Vitry, Old Polish Traditions in the Kitchen and at the Table (1979) and Lesley Chamberlain, The Food and Cooking of Eastern Europe (1989). The charred onion is a classic technique for colour and depth.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rosół is not a quick soup. It is a three-hour enterprise, the broth deepening slowly over a gentle heat that must never reach a full boil. A boiling rosół turns cloudy; a trembling simmer keeps it clear. The patience is the technique.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The charred onion is a traditional step. Hold an onion half over a gas flame with tongs (or char it cut-side down in a dry frying pan) until the cut face is blackened. It goes into the broth and gives a light, caramel-brown colour and a slightly sweet depth.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
