      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the pot",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Put the chicken into a large pot. Cover with 3 litres of cold water. Bring slowly to a simmer over medium-low heat, this takes about 20 minutes. As it approaches a simmer, grey foam will rise to the surface. Skim it off with a ladle, repeating until the surface is clear. Add all the vegetables, charred onion, garlic, herbs, and spices.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Simmer for 2 hours",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook at the gentlest possible simmer (the surface should just tremble) for 2 to 2.5 hours. Never let it boil. After 2 hours the chicken should be falling off the bone. Strain through a fine sieve into a clean pot. Season with salt. Pick the chicken meat from the bones and set aside. Slice the cooked carrots.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Serve over noodles",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the egg noodles separately according to the packet. Divide noodles and a few pieces of chicken and carrot between bowls. Ladle the clear hot broth over the top and scatter with freshly chopped parsley.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Next time, hold the heat at a bare simmer; cloudy broth still tastes fine, for a clear result next time, start with cold water and never let it boil hard",
              "cause": "Boiled at a rolling boil at some point during cooking",
              "symptom": "Broth is cloudy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Season assertively with salt only after straining; the flavour concentrated over 2 hours needs a proper amount of salt to come through",
              "cause": "Not seasoned at the end, or too much water",
              "symptom": "Broth tastes flat"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rosół is the Sunday soup. In Poland, Sunday lunch without rosół is almost unthinkable in the older generation. The broth comes first, served with homemade egg noodles; the boiled chicken follows as the second course. The soup has cultural weight far beyond its ingredients. It is the smell of a Polish grandmother's kitchen, the taste of recovery from illness, the meal that marks the beginning of a long family afternoon.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
